JIT-compile Exo language procedures to MLIR or native code.

Exo is a hardware-oriented programming language that lets users write
and optimize compute kernels with explicit control over scheduling and
memory, but it only generates C code.

xDSL is a Python-native compiler framework that provides MLIR-style
intermediate representations and dialect lowering without depending on
the full LLVM/MLIR C++ toolchain.

llvmlite (from the Numba project) exposes a lightweight interface to
LLVM's JIT engine for compiling LLVM IR to native machine code at
runtime.

This project connects all three: Exo kernels are lowered through
xDSL's MLIR dialects and then JIT-compiled to native code via
llvmlite, so you can go from a high-level Exo procedure to a callable
function in a single Python process.

usage:

    $ uv run xdsl-exo examples/demo.py  # mlir
    $ uv run python examples/demo.py    # native

how it works:

      Exo Python source
          v
      Exo LoopIR
          v
    - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  xDSL
      MLIR module
          v
      MLIR LLVM dialect
          v
    - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - llvmlite
      Native code

references:

- https://github.com/xdslproject/xdsl/blob/main/README.md
- https://github.com/exo-lang/exo/blob/main/docs/README.md
- https://github.com/kaylendog/exo-mlir
